04313nam a22006855i 9781487579593DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191984onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875795937 a10.3138/97814875795932doi  a(DE-B1597)527771  a(OCoLC)1129201165  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aBT708 7aREL0670702bisacsh04a241.6609022231 aPayer, Pierre J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSex and the Penitentials :bThe Development of a Sexual Code, 550-1150 /cPierre J. Payer. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1984  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Penitentials to 813 -- t2. The Ninth Century -- t3. Penitential Texts in Canonical Collections after 906 -- t4. General Conclusion -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tTables of Reference -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe sexual ethic of the early Christian church was simple: sexual relations were permitting only between a man and a woman married to one another and then only for the purpose of procreation. It soon became necessary to articulate and then to refine this ethnic, to analyse departures from it, and to provide for a range of penances suitable to each kind of sexual sin. The penitential -- a confessional manual for the guidance of the priest -- played an important role in this process. Payer argues, despite modern orthodoxy, that the penitentials reflect reaction to actual practice and are not simply a record of the wild imaginings of monkish minds or the abstract categorizing or legal minds. He traces the history of the penitentials from their early Irish origins in the sixth century through their ninth-century descendants in continental Europe and Anglo-Saxon England, to the great legal collections of the tenth and twelfth centuries. In the process he illuminates an increasingly sophisticated treatment of a wide variety of sexual situations, from the heterosexual life of the married and the unmarried, through homosexuality and lesbianism, bestiality, and masturbation, to the preservation of chastity. Sex and the Penitentials is a systematic inquiry into one of the richest sources of sexual teaching in the early church. It represents a major step towards an understanding of the nature of that teaching and its role in the transformation of the classical ethic into a Christian one.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPenitentials. 0aSexxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrinesyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aSocial historyyMedieval, 500-1500. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / Ethics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757959340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487579593423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487579593.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK